  🔠 call_00_WNftLTYL82OPx9SmZB4c8675 | Return {'content': '## Summary\n\nThis blog compares Apache Kafka and Redis Streams for real-time data streaming. It covers architectural differences, performance characteristics, use cases, and optimization techniques. Kafka excels in high-volume, long-retention, distributed scenarios, while Redis Streams offers sub-millisecond latency and simplicity for moderate data volumes within an existing Redis environment.\n\n## Key Points\n\n1. **Kafka** is a distributed streaming platform using disk-based storage for high durability and long retention (days to years); **Redis Streams** is an in-memory data structure (Redis 5.0+) with optional persistence, optimized for speed but constrained by RAM. (Source: Core Concepts sections)\n\n2. **Performance trade-off**: Redis Streams achieves sub-millisecond latency; Kafka offers higher throughput and scalability through partitioning and consumer groups. (Source: Key Differences table)\n\n3. **Choose Redis Streams** for <1TB/day, short retention, and simpler ops; **Choose Kafka** for >1TB/day, long-term storage, big data integrations (Hadoop, Spark), and cross-datacenter replication. (Source: Use Cases section)\n\n4. **Consumer groups**: Kafka assigns partitions statically with rebalance on failure; Redis Streams uses a PEL (Pending Entries List) and dynamic consumer handling. (Source: Technical Implementation)\n\n5. **Optimization tips**: For Redis, use `XTRIM MAXLEN ~1000` and batch message acknowledgements; for Kafka, tune `batch.size`, `linger.ms`, and partition count. (Source: Performance Optimization)\n\n6. **Scalability**: Kafka scales horizontally via partition distribution across brokers; Redis Streams scales via manual sharding or Redis Cluster. (Source: Scalability Approaches)\n\n## Technical Details\n\n**Redis Streams consumer group creation and reading:**\n```bash\nXGROUP CREATE mystream mygroup 0\nXREADGROUP GROUP mygroup consumer1 STREAMS mystream >\n```\n\n**Limiting stream length:**\n```bash\nXADD mystream MAXLEN ~ 1000 * field value\n```\n\n**Manual sharding pseudo-code for Redis Streams:**\n```python\nshard_id = hash_func(data) % num_of_shards\nredis_clients[shard_id].xadd(stream_name, data)\n```\n\n**Kafka Optimization Parameters:**\n- `batch.size` – trade-off between throughput and latency\n- `linger.ms` – batching delay\n- `fetch.min.bytes` and `fetch.max.wait.ms` – consumer fetch tuning\n- `max.poll.records` – control processing batch size\n\n## References & Citations\n\n- Blog source: [https://www.automq.com/blog/apache-kafka-vs-redis-streams-differences-and-comparison](https://www.automq.com/blog/apache-kafka-vs-redis-streams-differences-and-comparison)', 'links_on_page': ['https://www.automq.com/', 'https://www.automq.com/customers', 'https://www.automq.com/pricing', 'https://go.automq.com/slack', 'https://github.com/AutoMQ/automq', 'https://www.automq.com/contact', 'https://console.automq.cloud/?cta_location=header_desktop', 'https://www.automq.com/blog', 'https://console.automq.cloud/?utm_source=website&utm_medium=cta&utm_campaign=seo_blog', 'https://www.automq.com/customers', 'https://github.com/automq/automq', 'https://console.automq.cloud/?cta_location=blog_sidebar', 'https://www.automq.com/blog', 'https://www.automq.com/contact', 'https://www.automq.com/demo', 'https://go.automq.com/slack', 'https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.automq.com%2Fblog%2Fapache-kafka-vs-redis-streams-differences-and-comparison&text=Apache%20Kafka%20vs.%20Redis%20Streams%3A%20Differences%20%26%20Comparison', 'https://www.linkedin.com/sharing/share-offsite/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.automq.com%2Fblog%2Fapache-kafka-vs-redis-streams-differences-and-comparison', 'https://www.automq.com/demo', 'https://www.automq.com/executive-summary', 'https://trust.automq.com/', 'https://trust.automq.com/', 'https://www.automq.com/bring-your-own-cloud-kafka-data-streaming', 'https://www.automq.com/software-self-managed-kafka-data-streaming', 'https: