  🔠 call_01_yrIiHr7nfqQlc6pB4Bt57454 | Return {'content': '## Summary\n\nThis article provides a technical comparison of Redis Streams and Apache Kafka as event streaming solutions. It covers their operational models, persistence strategies, scalability ceilings, and code examples, concluding that Redis Streams suits moderate workloads on existing Redis infrastructure while Kafka is essential for durable, high-throughput, multi-partition streaming at scale.\n\n## Key Points\n\n1. **Persistence & Retention:** Redis Streams are in-memory with optional AOF, bounded by MAXLEN or memory; Kafka persists to disk with time/size-based retention (Source: "Side-by-Side Comparison" table).\n2. **Throughput & Scaling:** Redis Streams achieve ~100K msg/sec per stream; Kafka handles millions/sec across partitions (Source: same table).\n3. **Exactly-Once Semantics:** Kafka supports exactly-once via idempotent producer + transactions; Redis Streams do not (Source: same table).\n4. **Consumer Group Semantics:** Both support consumer groups, but Redis uses XPENDING for unacked messages, Kafka uses offsets. Redis provides total ordering within a stream; Kafka provides per-partition ordering (Source: "Redis Streams Basics", "Kafka Basics", and comparison table).\n5. **Backpressure Handling:** Redis uses `XADD ... MAXLEN ~ 10000` to cap stream size; Kafka configures retention via `kafka-configs.sh` (Source: "Handling Backpressure" section).\n6. **Dead Letter Handling:** Redis moves failed messages to a separate stream via `XADD` on error; Kafka uses `errors.deadletterqueue.topic.name` in Kafka Connect or custom consumer logic (Source: "Dead Letter Handling" section).\n\n## Technical Details\n\n**Redis Streams Commands (from article):**\n- Append: `XADD orders * user_id 42 item_id 100 qty 2`\n- Read without group: `XREAD COUNT 10 STREAMS orders 0-0`\n- Create consumer group: `XGROUP CREATE orders fulfillment $ MKSTREAM`\n- Consume: `XREADGROUP GROUP fulfillment worker1 COUNT 10 BLOCK 5000 STREAMS orders >`\n- Acknowledge: `XACK orders fulfillment 1700000000000-0`\n- Pending entries: `XPENDING orders fulfillment - + 10`\n\n**Kafka Producer (Java snippet):**\n```java\nProperties props = new Properties();\nprops.put("bootstrap.servers", "localhost:9092");\nprops.put("key.serializer", ...);\nprops.put("value.serializer", ...);\nProducer<String, String> producer = new KafkaProducer<>(props);\nproducer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("orders", "user-42", "{\\"item_id\\":100,\\"qty\\":2}"));\n```\n\n**Kafka Consumer (Java snippet):**\n```java\nProperties consumerProps = new Properties();\nconsumerProps.put("group.id", "fulfillment");\nconsumerProps.put("enable.auto.commit", "false");\nConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(consumerProps);\nconsumer.subscribe(Collections.singletonList("orders"));\nConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(5000));\nconsumer.commitSync();\n```\n\n**Backpressure Examples:**\n- Redis: `XADD orders MAXLEN ~ 10000 * user_id 42 item_id 100`\n- Kafka CLI: `kafka-configs.sh --alter --entity-type topics --entity-name orders --add-config "retention.ms=604800000,retention.bytes=10737418240"`\n\n**Dead Letter Logic (Redis):** Python function that catches exception, adds to DLQ stream with error info, then XACKs the original.\n\n## References & Citations\n\n- URL: https://oneuptime.com/blog/post/2026-03-31-redis-streams-vs-kafka-detailed-comparison/view\n- Sections: "Redis Streams Basics", "Kafka Basics", "Side-by-Side Comparison", "Handling Backpressure", "Dead Letter Handling", "When to Choose Redis Streams", "When to Choose Kafka", "Summary"', 'links_on_page': ['https://oneuptime.com/', 'https://oneuptime.com/product/monitoring', 'https://oneuptime.com/product/status-page', 'https://oneuptime.com/product/incident-management', 'https://oneuptime.com/product/on-call', 'https://oneuptime.com/product/scheduled-maintenance', 'https://oneuptime.com/product/logs-management', 'https://oneuptime.com/p